    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-10-04T18:00:00-05:00" n="1214"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1214">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.633/10–449: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Peiping</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clubb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-10-04T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 4, 1949—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>682. In view recent developments Peiping<note n="93" xml:id="d1214fn93">For
                        information on establishment on October 1 of Communist “Central People’s
                        Government of the People’s Republic of China”, see telegram No. 1666,
                        October 1, from the Consul General at Peiping, <ref target="#pg_544">p.
                            544</ref>.</note> Dept believes it desirable, unless you perceive
                    objection thereto, that you informally and in personal capacity approach Chou
                        En-lai<note n="94" xml:id="d1214fn94">Premier and Foreign Minister of the
                        Communist regime at Peiping.</note> by such means as you consider desirable
                    re evacuation Mukden ConGen staff. While Dept leaves substance to ur judgment,
                    it believes that you might call attn to approaching winter and express earnest
                    hope staff be permitted leave prior to incidence cold weather which under
                    existing conditions wld impose extreme hardship endanger health staff.<note
                        n="95" xml:id="d1214fn95">For information on action taken, see telegram No.
                        1707, October 10, 3 p. m., from the Consul General at Peiping, <ref
                            target="frus1949v09#pg_117">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ix</hi>, p.
                            117</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
